00:49:38.791 --> 00:49:42.180
I don't know.

00:49:42.180 --> 00:49:44.960
Beer can chicken.

00:49:44.960 --> 00:49:47.060
Everybody know what
a beer koozie is?

00:49:47.060 --> 00:49:50.550
A little piece of foam rubber
that you put around a beer can,

00:49:50.550 --> 00:49:53.810
and it's supposed to
keep your beer cold?

00:49:53.810 --> 00:49:56.930
What do you think a 38 degree
three and a half pound chicken

00:49:56.930 --> 00:49:57.950
is?

00:49:57.950 --> 00:50:00.430
It's a chicken koozie.

00:50:00.430 --> 00:50:02.420
It keeps the beer cold.

00:50:02.420 --> 00:50:04.280
You put it up the
butt of the chicken.

00:50:04.280 --> 00:50:07.140
And now you have a
large thermal mass

00:50:07.140 --> 00:50:09.810
that comes out of the
refrigerator at 38 degrees.

00:50:09.810 --> 00:50:13.900
The beer never gets beyond
the temperature of the meat.

00:50:13.900 --> 00:50:14.940
It can't.

00:50:14.940 --> 00:50:16.300
It doesn't boil.

00:50:16.300 --> 00:50:17.790
It doesn't steam.

00:50:17.790 --> 00:50:20.220
Steaming temperature
is 212 degrees.

00:50:20.220 --> 00:50:24.460
If you cook the meat
safely to 160-165 degrees,

00:50:24.460 --> 00:50:29.590
the beer rarely goes above 150.

00:50:29.590 --> 00:50:31.540
If you overcook
the hell out of it,

00:50:31.540 --> 00:50:34.040
blacken it, and take it
up to 190 or something,

00:50:34.040 --> 00:50:37.100
the beer still won't
go over 190 degrees.

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:37.910
It can't boil.

00:50:37.910 --> 00:50:40.330
You weigh the can
before, you weigh the can

00:50:40.330 --> 00:50:42.210
after, it weighs the same.

00:50:42.210 --> 00:50:45.000
In fact, in a few
cases, when we tried it,

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:46.400
we weighed the can after it.

00:50:46.400 --> 00:50:48.910
It actually weighed
more because the fat

00:50:48.910 --> 00:50:51.849
from the chicken dripped into
the can, coated the surface,

00:50:51.849 --> 00:50:53.640
and of course, that
went further to prevent

00:50:53.640 --> 00:50:55.840
the beer from evaporating.

00:50:55.840 --> 00:50:57.510
So beer can chicken is cool.

00:50:57.510 --> 00:50:58.330
It looks cool.

00:50:58.330 --> 00:50:59.788
I mean, doesn't
that little chicken

00:50:59.788 --> 00:51:02.800
sitting there looking like
a human being look cool?

00:51:02.800 --> 00:51:04.860
But then the beer can
chicken devotees say,

00:51:04.860 --> 00:51:07.030
but everybody loves
my beer can chicken.

00:51:07.030 --> 00:51:07.740
It's so good.

00:51:07.740 --> 00:51:09.020
It's delicious.

00:51:09.020 --> 00:51:10.210
Of course it's delicious.

00:51:10.210 --> 00:51:11.450
It's roast chicken.

00:51:11.450 --> 00:51:13.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:13.260 --> 00:51:15.740
Everybody loves roast chicken.

00:51:15.740 --> 00:51:19.660
It's hard to mess up roast
chicken unless you overcook it.

00:51:19.660 --> 00:51:22.690
Only it's not roasted
as well as it could be.

00:51:22.690 --> 00:51:25.710
If you take the beer can out,
warm air will enter the center.

00:51:25.710 --> 00:51:28.200
And it will cook from the
inside as well as the outside.

00:51:28.200 --> 00:51:30.360
You won't over
cook the exterior.

00:51:30.360 --> 00:51:33.910
In fact, for me, I'll
cut it into quarters.

00:51:33.910 --> 00:51:35.540
Cut it up into pieces.

00:51:35.540 --> 00:51:37.220
Cook the pieces separately.

00:51:37.220 --> 00:51:41.340
That way, you can brown both
sides, not just the exterior.

00:51:41.340 --> 00:51:43.820
You can get maximum brown.

00:51:43.820 --> 00:51:45.380
And you can temp
each piece of meat

00:51:45.380 --> 00:51:47.490
individually and get
each piece of meat

00:51:47.490 --> 00:51:50.100
off at the optimum temperature.

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:52.370
So beer can chicken
may be delicious.

00:51:52.370 --> 00:51:55.250
But it's far from the best
way of cooking chicken.

00:51:55.250 --> 00:51:58.040
It does look cool though.

00:51:58.040 --> 00:52:00.150
Anybody hate me now?

